To address the issue of the mobile browser not entering fullscreen mode when scrolled due to your fixed navigation component, you'll want to make changes to encourage the browser's address bar to auto-hide on scroll.

Here's a possible approach to modify your `<Nav />` component so that it behaves better on mobile:

1. Consider alternative positioning for the navigation bar, such as changing it from `fixed` to `sticky`. This can allow the browser UI to behave more naturally.

2. Ensure that the `height` property on mobile is not set to a value that disrupts the natural full-screen behavior. Avoid using `height: 100vh` because it might not account for the mobile browser's address bar.

3. To enable the hiding of the browser address bar when scrolling, ensure your navigation bar is not too tall; otherwise, it might prevent this auto-hide feature from triggering.

If you've tried everything and the browser still won't enter fullscreen mode due to the navigation bar, as a last resort, you might opt for a UI design that minimizes or hides the navigation bar on scroll. You can do this with some JavaScript:

```javascript
function hideNavBarOnScroll() {
  let lastScrollTop = 0;
  window.addEventListener("scroll", function () {
    let currentScroll = window.pageYOffset || document.documentElement.scrollTop;
    if (currentScroll > lastScrollTop) {
      // Scrolling down, hide the nav
      document.querySelector('nav').style.bottom = '-80px'; // adjust -80px to the height of your nav
    } else {
      // Scrolling up, show the nav
      document.querySelector('nav').style.bottom = '0';
    }
    lastScrollTop = currentScroll <= 0 ? 0 : currentScroll; // For Mobile or negative scrolling
  }, false);
}

document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded", hideNavBarOnScroll);
```

Add this script to your component, and adjust the `style.bottom` values to correspond to your navigation bar's height. However, be careful with this approach as it may affect UX by making navigation less accessible.

Please ensure that you test these changes across different devices and browsers to make sure they work as intended and that they don't create any new issues with your layout on mobile.

