To refactor your Next.js navigation component to include a mobile navigation toggle, you will need to:
- Add state to track whether the mobile menu is open
- Implement a button to toggle this state
- Modify the navigation rendering to show or hide based on the state
- Optionally, apply some additional styling and transitions for a smoother user experience

Below you'll find a refactored version of your code including a simple nav toggle implementation:

```javascript
import Link from "next/link";
import { useState } from "react";
import { usePathname } from "next/navigation";

// icons
import { GrBusinessService } from "react-icons/gr";
import { BsPersonWorkspace, BsFillChatLeftHeartFill } from "react-icons/bs";
import { HiHomeModern } from "react-icons/hi2";
import { SiAffinitydesigner } from "react-icons/si";
import { GrMail } from "react-icons/gr";

// nav data
export const navData = [
  { name: "home", path: "/", Icon: HiHomeModern },
  { name: "about", path: "/about", Icon: BsPersonWorkspace },
  { name: "services", path: "/services", Icon: GrBusinessService },
  { name: "designs", path: "/designs", Icon: SiAffinitydesigner },
  { name: "testimonials", path: "/testimonials", Icon: BsFillChatLeftHeartFill },
  { name: "contact", path: "/contact", Icon: GrMail },
];

const Nav = () => {
  const pathname = usePathname();
  const [isNavOpen, setIsNavOpen] = useState(false);

  const handleNavToggle = () => {
    setIsNavOpen(!isNavOpen);
  };

  return (
    <nav className="relative">
      <button onClick={handleNavToggle} className="absolute right-0 top-0 z-50">
        {isNavOpen ? 'Close' : 'Menu'}
      </button>
      <div className={`flex flex-col items-center xl:justify-center gap-y-4 sticky h-max z-40 top-0 w-full transition-transform transform ${
        isNavOpen ? "translate-x-0" : "translate-x-full"
      } xl:translate-x-0`}>
        {/* Your existing nav content */}
        <div className="flex w-full xl:flex-col items-center justify-between xl:justify-center gap-y-10 px-4 md:px-40 xl:px-0 h-[80px] xl:h-max py-8 bg-white/10 backdrop-blur-sm text-3xl xl:text-xl xl:rounded-full">
          {navData.map((link, i) => (
            <Link
              className={`${
                link.path === pathname ? "text-accent" : ""
              } relative flex items-center group hover:text-accent transition-all duration-300`}
              href={link.path}
              key={i}
            >
              <a onClick={() => isNavOpen && setIsNavOpen(false)}> {/* Close the nav on click when open */}
                {/* Tooltip and icon */}
                <div>{link.name}</div>
              </a>
            </Link>
          ))}
        </div>
      </div>
    </nav>
  );
};

export default Nav;
```

This implementation includes:
- A button to toggle the menu (with text that changes between "Menu" and "Close")
- A state variable `isNavOpen` that determines if the mobile menu should be open
- A class `translate-x-0` for "menu open" and `translate-x-full` for "menu closed" state to move the menu in and out of view (you may need to adjust this based on your structure and styling)
- Wrapping each `Link` content in an additional `<a>` tag to add an `onClick` handler that closes the navigation when a link is clicked on mobile

