The error you're encountering is related to CSS Modules where the use of `[data-*]` attribute selectors without a class or ID is not allowed. CSS Modules require that each selector be "local" (scoped to the component) by default; thus, they must contain a local class or id. 

To fix the syntax error and maintain the scoping of your CSS Module, you must prepend a local class to the attribute selector. 

Here's the corrected code with the local class `.icon` added before the attribute selectors:

```css
@layer layout {
  .toggle {
    /* Your existing .toggle styles */
  }

  .inner {
    /* Your existing .inner styles */
  }

  .icon {
    /* Your existing .icon styles */

    /* Change here: Added .icon before the attribute selectors */
    &.icon[data-open='true'] {
      opacity: 0;

      @media (--mediaUseMotion) {
        transition-delay: 0s;
        transform: rotate(45deg);
      }
    }

    &.icon[data-close='true'] {
      opacity: 0;

      @media (--mediaUseMotion) {
        transition-delay: 0s;
        transform: rotate(-45deg);
      }
    }

    &.icon[data-open='true'][data-close='true'] {
      opacity: 1;

      @media (--mediaUseMotion) {
        transition-delay: 0.1s;
        transform: rotate(0deg);
      }
    }
  }
}
```

As you can see, I've prepended the local class `.icon` to each of the attribute selectors. This maintains the modular scope of your styles and should fix the syntax error.

The corrected selectors are now considered "pure" because they involve a local class rather than just attribute selectors, thus adhering to CSS Modules' requirements.

Make sure to test the changes after this fix to ensure that styles are applied correctly and that your layout continues to behave as expected.

